{"title":"IMPACT: Iterative Mask-based Parallel Decoding for Text-to-Audio Generation with Diffusion Modeling","domain":"SPEECH","seeds":[{"problem":"Diffusion-based text-to-audio models achieve high fidelity but suffer from slow inference due to multi-step sampling with heavy attention backbones, while mask-based models on discrete tokens (e.g., MAGNET) are fast but lag in audio quality/fidelity.","method":"IMPACT integrates iterative mask-based parallel decoding into a latent diffusion model operating on continuous audio latents. Audio is encoded with a VAE; during training, masked latents are reconstructed by a Transformer-based latent encoder conditioned on text and a lightweight MLP diffusion head that predicts noise only at masked positions. At inference, it decodes from an empty sequence using random position selection (no confidence scores in continuous space) and a cosine mask schedule, with diffusion sampling and classifier-free guidance. Replacing heavy attention diffusion cores with the small MLP head and leveraging parallel decoding yields low latency while preserving diffusion fidelity, achieving state-of-the-art FD and FAD on AudioCaps and competitive or better latency vs. MAGNET-S depending on iteration settings."},{"problem":"Text-conditional training must simultaneously learn audio generation and text alignment, but paired text–audio data is limited, reducing fidelity and text relevance.","method":"IMPACT introduces an unconditional pre-training phase (mask-based generative modeling without text) on large unpaired audio (e.g., AudioSet), followed by text-conditional training. This curriculum first imparts general audio generative ability, then aligns to text, enabling the use of much larger datasets. Ablations show unconditional pre-training is indispensable: models with pre-training consistently improve FD/FAD and human REL/OVL ratings, with larger-scale pre-training further boosting fidelity despite minor trade-offs on some metrics."}]}
